    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-05-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-05-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="607"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d607">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115/3446</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at London</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRP1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-05-26">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 26, 1915</hi>.</date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 6 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department’s 3d<note n="1" xml:id="d607fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_379">p. 379</ref>.</note> and
                        7th.<note n="2" xml:id="d607fn2">Not printed.</note>
                    <hi rend="italic">Ogeechee</hi> case. Procurator general after consulting
                    Foreign Office writes:</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>Foreign office unable see any reason why proceedings should not take usual
                        course, and I may point out that goods fall within jurisdiction of prize
                        court. When vessel detained by executive authority comes under provisions
                        order in council, it is not in my power, but must rest with Secretary of
                        State to grant permission to continue voyage without discharging cargo. With
                        regard your proposal that I suggest expeditious manner clearing up <hi
                            rend="italic">Ogeechee</hi>, I should be glad to do what is possible. I
                        should be prepared to consider any evidence which claimants produce to show
                        that goods had become property citizens of United States before issue of
                        order in council, with view to release goods without action under clause
                        five. In proper cases I should myself be prepared to take necessary
                        steps.</p>
                </quote>
                <p>In view of foregoing, renew my recommendation May 3 [5] and 8.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d607fn3">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_380">pp. 380</ref> and <ref
                            target="#pg_385">385</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SRP1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Skinner</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
